Builds the type and construct tables that power the programmatic (`dict.infinite.steno`) corpus path, bypassing Pass B enumeration entirely. Instead of generating rows, it records template structure and slot positions; at query time, `walk` replays type-append by walking the obligation stack, with cost proportional to strokes pressed, not `O(T^s)`. See `docs/pipeline.md`.

`InfType` holds a `@type` entry's stroke, generic arity, and rendered text with `%t` markers. `Construct` holds a count-resolved Pass-A entry's base segments, optional fuse shape, template with slot chunks intact, slot indices in template order, and fill order (D12: fuse-target first for fused constructs, otherwise template order). Both are records, not generators.

`build_types(entries)` filters `@type` entries and renders their templates via `render_type_text`, which rejects anything but `Lit` and `TypeSlot` chunks. `build_constructs(entries)` runs `expand_counts` on non-`@type` entries and builds one `Construct` per count-resolved output. `build_tables` runs both.

`check_fuse_ambiguity(types, constructs)` is a build-time safety check (criterion 5): no two `(shape, type)` pairs may merge to the same stroke under the same base. Enumeration would catch this as an output collision, but infinite replay emits no rows, so it must be checked explicitly or an ambiguous fuse silently produces wrong lookups. The check is `O(constructs × types)` and errors with both colliding pairs named.